[[File:Alps from space.png|thumb|right|260px|The Alps from space in 2002.]]
The '''Alps''' ({{lang-de|Alpen}}; {{lang-it|Alpi}}; {{lang-lmo|Alp}}; {{lang-fr|Alpes}}; {{lang-oc|Aups/Alps}}; {{lang-rm|Alps}}; {{lang-sl|Alpe}})  is one of the great [[mountain range]] systems of [[Europe]], stretching from [[Austria]] and [[Slovenia]] in the east through [[Italy]], [[Switzerland]], [[Liechtenstein]] and [[Germany]] to [[France]] in the west.

The highest mountain in the Alps is [[Mont Blanc]], at {{Convert|4810.45|m|ft|0}},&lt;ref name=&quot;smh4810.45&quot;&gt;{{cite news | url = http://www.smh.com.au/environment/mont-blanc-shrinks-by-45cm-in-two-years-20091106-i0kk.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Mont Blanc shrinks by 45cm in two years | date=6 November 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; on the Italian–French border. All the main peaks of the Alps can be found in the [[list of mountains of the Alps]] and [[list of Alpine peaks by prominence]].

==Etymology==

The English name ''Alps'' was taken via [[French language|French]] from [[Latin]] ''Alpes'', which may be ultimately cognate with Latin ''albus'' (&quot;white&quot;). The German ''Albe'', ''Alpe'' or ''Alp'' (f., [[Old High German]] ''alpâ'', plural ''alpûn''), the Occitan ''Alp''/''Aup''&lt;ref&gt;[[Frederic Mistral]], ''Lou Tresor dóu Felibrige'': &quot;AUP, ALP: Alpe, haute montagne particulièrement propre à faire paître les troupeaux&quot;, high mountain particularly suited for grazing herds.&lt;/ref&gt; and the French ''Alpage'' or ''Alpe'' in the singular mean &quot;[[alpine pasture]]&quot;, and only in the plural may also refer to the mountain range as a whole.&lt;ref&gt;[[Jacob Grimm]], ''[[Deutsches Wörterbuch]]'', s.v. &quot;Albe&quot;, &quot;Alpe&quot;. The original meaning being &quot;white&quot; (in reference to the [[permanent snow]]. The term may be common [[Italo-Celtic]], since [[Celtic languages]] also have terms for high mountains derived from ''alp''. German ''Alpen'' is the accusative in origin, but was made the nominative in Modern German, whence also ''Alm''.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Geography==
{{main|Geography of the Alps}}


The highest peak of the Western Alps is [[Mont Blanc]], at {{Convert|4810.45|m|ft|0}}.&lt;ref name=&quot;smh4810.45&quot; /&gt; The highest peak of the Eastern Alps is [[Piz Bernina]] at {{convert|4049|m|ft|0}}. [[Monte Rosa]] at {{convert|4634|m|ft|0}}. and [[Ortler]],&lt;ref&gt;Excluding the [[Piz Zupò]] and [[Piz Roseg]] located in the Bernina range, close to Piz Bernina.&lt;/ref&gt; {{convert|3905|m|ft|0}}, are the second-highest, respectively.

The '''Eastern Alps''' is commonly subdivided according to the different [[lithology]] (rock composition) of the more central parts of the Alps and the groups at its northern and southern fringes:

* [[Northern Limestone Alps]] (from the [[Wienerwald]] to [[Bregenzerwald]]), including the [[Flyschzone]]; peaks up to {{convert|3000|m|ft|-1}}
* [[Central Eastern Alps]] (Austria, Switzerland); peaks up to {{convert|4050|m|ft|-1}}
* [[Southern Limestone Alps]] (Austria, Italy, Slovenia)
The border between the Central Alps and the Southern Limestone Alps is the [[Periadriatic Seam]]. The Northern Limestone Alps are separated from the Central Eastern Alps by the [[Greywacke zone]].

The '''Western Alps''' is commonly subdivided with respect to [[geography]]:
* [[Ligurian Alps]]
* [[Maritime Alps]]
* [[Cottian Alps]]
* [[Dauphiné Alps]]
* [[Graian Alps]]
* [[Chablais Alps]]
* [[Pennine Alps]]
* [[Bernese Alps]]
* [[Lepontine Alps]]
* [[Glarus Alps]]
* [[Appenzell Alps]].
Series of lower mountain ranges run parallel to the main chain of the Alps, including the [[French Prealps]]. (See [[Geography of the Alps|Alpine geography]].)

The geologic subdivision is different and makes no difference between the Western and Eastern Alps: the [[Helvetic nappes|Helveticum]] in the north, the [[Penninic nappes|Penninicum]] and [[Austroalpine nappes|Austroalpine system]] in the center and, south of the Periadriatic Seam, the [[Southern Alps (geology)|Southern Alpine system]] and parts of the [[Dinarides]] (see [[Geology of the Alps|Alpine geology]]). Geographically, the [[Jura Mountains]] do not belong to the Alps; geologically, however, they do.

===Main chain===
{{main|Main chain of the Alps}}
[[File:Hauteroute.jpg|thumb|The watershed between Italy and Switzerland (View from [[Tête Blanche]], Pennine Alps)]]
The secondary chain of the Alps follows the [[drainage divide|watershed]] from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the [[Wienerwald]], passing over many of the highest and most famous peaks in the Alps. From the Colle di Cadibona to [[Col de Tende]] it runs westwards, before turning to the northwest and then, near the [[Colle della Maddalena]], to the north. Upon reaching the Swiss border, the line of the main chain heads approximately east-northeast, a heading it follows until its end near [[Vienna]].

===Principal passes===
{{main|Principal passes of the Alps}}

The Alps does not form an impassable barrier; It has been traversed for war and [[commerce]], and later by [[pilgrim]]s, students and tourists. Crossing places by road, train or foot are called ''passes''. These are depressions in the mountains into which a valley leads from the plains and hilly pre-mountainous zones.

==Four-thousanders==
{{see also|List of Alpine Four-thousanders}}
The [[Union Internationale des Associations d'Alpinisme]] (UIAA) has defined a list of 82 &quot;official&quot; Alpine 4,000-metre (13,123&amp;nbsp;ft) summits. The list contains many subpeaks with little [[Topographic prominence|prominence]], but important for [[mountaineering]]. Here are the twelve [[four-thousanders]] with at least 1&amp;nbsp;km prominence.

